Consider your application as a whole. What do you personally want to emphasize about your application for the admission committee’s consideration? Highlight something that’s important to you or something you haven’t had a chance to share. Tell us, don’t show us (no websites please). (300 Words)
Gospel music brings me peace. I have heard my mom sing it for my whole life, and I knew that I wanted to learn how to play it on the piano. Although I had been playing classical music on the piano since age five, when I started playing gospel music in ninth grade, my musical ability improved. 
    I learned to play gospel music by ear, which is the best way to do so. The idea is to adapt to the singer through accompaniment. Doing this has taught me how to improvise, allowing me to explore a song, rather than being bound to the notes on sheet music. It also taught me how to observe melodies, splitting up different parts until I find the bass line, and to learn the music simply. 
    When I started playing gospel songs at church, the other musicians were excited. I was never nervous playing with them, because they would always keep me in rhythm. Even when the church went online during the pandemic, I still submitted songs to be played during the service. My mother or sister sang, or sometimes, I sang while playing the piano. I was glad that this was something I could continue over the pandemic. Once we reopened, I was honored to play Amazing Grace in a candlelight service that acknowledged the 183 individuals in my neighborhood who had passed due to COVID-19 complications. 
    Gospel music has transformed my way of thinking. I can slow down and explore topics to learn with more depth. I understand now that these topics broken into parts foster the most cumulative learning. Playing gospel music allows me to be in the moment, which calms my mind and gives me mental clarity.

In William Shakespeare's play "Hamlet," the titular character is driven by a desire for justice and a need to avenge the murder of his father, the former king of Denmark. As the play progresses, however, Hamlet's focus shifts from seeking justice to pursuing revenge.

At the beginning of the play, Hamlet is consumed by grief and anger at the news of his father's murder. He is determined to uncover the truth and bring the perpetrators to justice. He even contemplates suicide as a way to escape his pain and suffering.

As Hamlet investigates the murder, he becomes increasingly convinced that his uncle, Claudius, is responsible. He becomes obsessed with finding evidence and proof of Claudius' guilt, and his desire for justice consumes him.

However, as Hamlet's plans for revenge take shape, his actions become more and more extreme. He manipulates and deceives those around him, including his loved ones, in order to achieve his goals. He becomes consumed by his desire for revenge, and it begins to cloud his judgment and moral compass.

Eventually, Hamlet's actions have tragic consequences, as those around him are caught in the crossfire of his pursuit of revenge. The once-noble prince becomes consumed by his own anger and hatred, and his actions ultimately lead to the downfall of his family and the destruction of the kingdom.

In the end, Hamlet's shift from justice to revenge serves as a cautionary tale about the dangers of allowing one's emotions to consume them. It serves as a reminder of the importance of staying true to one's principles and values, even in the face of great adversity.

In Act III, Laertes tells Ophelia the dangers of Hamlet. He warns Ophelia that Hamlet can backstab him if he shows affection, so Laertes suggests to her to “be wary then; best safety lies in fear” (1.3.48). When Laertes says “best safety”, he stresses that there can be no chances taken. Laertes doesn’t give her a list of options to stay safe; he only gives one option. The safety “lies in fear”, which implies a resting nature to the safety, but in a dangerous place. One cannot sleep in a dangerous place. This may imply, according to Laetes, that if Hamlet seems to be trust-worthy, Ophelia’s safety should never deeply sleep. One cannot live without sleeping, so Hamlet decides to confront his supposed fear head on. After the ghost invites Hamlet to come with him, Horatio fears that following the ghost will lead him into treachery. Hamlet responds, “Why, what should be the fear” (1.3.48)?  Hamlet says “the fear” which downplays Horatio’s caution to one cause. “In fear”, said by Laertes, emphasizes the area of fear. Fear should surround Ophelia, while Hamlet implies that he can match the one fearful thing. Both Hamlet and Ophelia are being warned of fear, yet probably don’t heed the warning. Ophelia cannot lie awake in fear forever and Hamlet is confident in what he does. Fear is a lurking sensation for both, yet they do not let fear drive them.
